<TITLE> North Korea still wants nuclear deal: US envoy </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 SEOUL, Jan 9 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - North Korea is still committed to an international disarmament-for-aid deal, a US nuclear envoy said on Wednesday, urging patience even though the reclusive state missed a deadline to list its nuclear arms programme. Under a deal it reached with regional powers, North Korea was supposed to provide by the end of 2007 an inventory of its fissile material and nuclear weaponry and answer US suspicions it had a secret programme to enrich uranium for weapons. "We are not that far apart. I don't think it is something we want to walk away from nor does the DPRK (North Korea) want to walk away from this," US Assistant Secretary of State Christopher Hill told reporters in Seoul. "We didn't meet the timeframe. We ought to be a little patient on this." Hill is travelling through Northeast Asia and Russia to discuss the deal, which would give North Korea 1 million tonnes of heavy fuel oil or equivalent aid, as well as removing it from a US terrorism blacklist, if it makes the declaration and starts taking apart a nuclear facility that produces arms-grade plutonium. Hill said the disablement of the North's Soviet-era nuclear reactor, a plant the produces nuclear fuel and another that turns spent fuel into plutonium has been going smoothly. That process started in early November and is the first tangible step the North has made it roll back its nuclear arms programme since it began in earnest its quest for the weapons in the 1980s. Hill said the United States wanted to make a complete list and it will exercise goodwill if Pyongyang makes such a declaration. He paid a courtesy call on South Korean President Roh Moo-hyun, who leaves office next month and discussed the nuclear situation. "We just talked about the need to finish this job ... because the job will not be finished until we get complete denuclearisation," he said. Hill will meet South Korean President-elect Lee Myung-bak on Thursday and then travel to Beijing. His final stop is Mosc
